the note on chapter vi.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#note8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the note on chapter iii.5</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
Early in 320 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
Antigonus had corrupted Apollonides, commander of a division of cavalry under Eumenes, and he went over to the


<A ID="p105x"></A>enemy in the midst of battle, with his division. <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18B*.html#40.5
	"TARGET="Diodorus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Diodorus,WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Diodorus, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVIII</SPAN>.40.5‑8</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
Many deserted to Antigonus, according to Diodorus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18B*.html#41
	"TARGET="Diodorus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Diodorus,WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">XVIII</SPAN>.41.1)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
This device of Eumenes is described also in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18B*.html#42.3
	"TARGET="Diodorus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Diodorus,WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Diodorus, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVIII</SPAN>.42.3 f.</A>, and in
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/nepos/nepos.eum.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Nepos\' life of Eumenes'+Lat2+LatSearch+'iumentum</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nepos, <I>Eumenes</I>, v.4 f.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
In 320 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> After the death of Perdiccas the supreme regency devolved upon Antipater, and he retired into Macedonia with the two kings. On his death he left the regency


<A ID="p115x"></A>to Polysperchon, a distinguished officer of Alexander, to the exclusion of his own son Cassander.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify" ID="note27">
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref27a
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27a</A>
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref27b
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27b</A>
See the notes on chapter <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#note6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">iii.1
	</A>
and <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#note10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A>. Olympias was the <SPAN CLASS="whole">queen-mother</SPAN>, the widow of Philip, mother of Alexander.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
Philip Arrhidaeus (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#note6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the note on chapter iii.1</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
Or Cyinda, better known as Anazarbus, a stronghold in Cilicia, whither Antigenes and Teutamus had brought the royal treasure from Susa.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
In 317 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, against Antigonus, who was in Mesopotamia. He had received the satrapy of Susiana.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
One of the most distinguished officers of Alexander,


<A ID="p119x"></A>who had been made satrap of Persia during Alexander's lifetime.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
These events are more fully and very differently described by Diodorus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19B*.html#24
	"TARGET="Diodorus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Diodorus,WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">XIX</SPAN>.24‑32)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#13.6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chapter xiii.6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
According to Nepos
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/nepos/nepos.eum.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Cornelius Nepos\' life of Eumenes'+Lat2+LatSearch+'custodibus</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Eumenes</I>, xii.4)</A>, Eumenes was


<A ID="p137x"></A>strangled by his keepers, without the knowledge of Antigonus.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:house_14_cubits_long" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref:house_14_cubits_long
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
Fourteen cubits, or <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-one</SPAN> feet, is about 4 meters. Now these houses may have been small — as houses often are in Mediterranean and Middle Eastern villages, all clumped together behind defensive walls and with an eye to shade and conserving resources — but this is just too small to be right. If as stated, Nora, the place they were stuck in, measured two stadia (just over 350 meters) in circumference, its area must have been something like 6000 to 7000 m<SPAN CLASS="superscript">2</SPAN>, just about that of a regulation American football field; and there would be room for a larger house than that. In <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#10.1.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10.1</A>, furthermore, Plutarch states that those who took refuge in Nora numbered 700, not counting those horses, stores of grain, the thickness of the walls of several houses, and some slight open space between them: so that even 7000 m<SPAN CLASS="superscript">2</SPAN> is almost certainly wrong as well. In sum, the figures in the text cannot be right, and there has surely been a manuscript transmission problem here.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Polysperchon" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Eumenes*.html#ref:Polysperchon
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
The modern consensus, by and large, is that the man's name was <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">Polyperchon</SPAN> (no <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">s</SPAN>). Perrin will spell his name <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">Polysperchon</SPAN>, however, thruout the <I>Phocion</I> and <I>Eumenes</I>, as well as once in the <I>Pyrrhus</I>; shifting to the other spelling in the <I>Demetrius</I>. For the man himself, a good article may be found, as so often, at Livius, <I>s.v.</I> <A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/person/polyperchon/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Polyperchon</A>.



